WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.020 --> 00:00:02.865
Alright, let's talk about something that might seem kind

2
00:00:02.865 --> 00:00:05.025
of small, but is actually a huge deal

3
00:00:05.125 --> 00:00:07.745
for a well-built website headings.

4
00:00:08.245 --> 00:00:09.345
Now I know what you're thinking.

5
00:00:09.375 --> 00:00:11.825
They're just big, bold text, right?

6
00:00:12.175 --> 00:00:14.465
Well, not exactly as we're about to see,

7
00:00:14.475 --> 00:00:16.745
there may be the most important tool we have

8
00:00:16.745 --> 00:00:19.825
for making content easy to navigate for everyone.

9
00:00:20.375 --> 00:00:23.185
Okay? To really get this, let's use a simple metaphor.

10
00:00:23.495 --> 00:00:25.985
Imagine I hand you a book, the one on the left,

11
00:00:26.295 --> 00:00:27.745
it's got clear chapters, right?

12
00:00:28.005 --> 00:00:29.825
You can easily flip to whatever you need,

13
00:00:30.125 --> 00:00:33.025
but the one on the right, it's just a solid block of text.

14
00:00:33.325 --> 00:00:34.625
No chapters, no sections.

15
00:00:34.915 --> 00:00:36.505
Which one would you even want to read?

16
00:00:37.055 --> 00:00:39.145
Well, for a lot of people, this is exactly

17
00:00:39.145 --> 00:00:40.945
what the web feels like when it doesn't have a good

18
00:00:41.065 --> 00:00:43.905
structure, and that quote just hits the nail on the head.

19
00:00:44.365 --> 00:00:46.665
You know, for someone using a screen reader, someone

20
00:00:46.725 --> 00:00:48.945
who can't see all the visual stuff, like big fonts

21
00:00:48.945 --> 00:00:51.025
and spacing, a page without headings

22
00:00:51.035 --> 00:00:52.345
isn't just a little annoying.

23
00:00:52.525 --> 00:00:53.985
It can be a total deal breaker,

24
00:00:54.375 --> 00:00:56.745
just an impossible wall of text.

25
00:00:57.685 --> 00:00:59.985
So yeah, let's really dig into that first idea.

26
00:01:00.505 --> 00:01:03.145
A book without chapters. What's it actually like?

27
00:01:03.145 --> 00:01:05.665
Trying to find your way around when there are no signposts,

28
00:01:05.765 --> 00:01:07.185
no map, just words.

29
00:01:07.925 --> 00:01:08.985
You know, when you

30
00:01:09.045 --> 00:01:12.185
or I look at a page, our brains do this amazing thing.

31
00:01:12.205 --> 00:01:16.825
Almost instantly we see a visual hierarchy. Big, bold text.

32
00:01:17.135 --> 00:01:18.505
Okay, that's an important section.

33
00:01:18.975 --> 00:01:21.345
Smaller text underneath, that's a subsection.

34
00:01:21.925 --> 00:01:25.105
We just get it. But a screen reader needs a completely

35
00:01:25.105 --> 00:01:26.305
different kind of map.

36
00:01:26.605 --> 00:01:28.425
One that's literally written into the code.

37
00:01:28.685 --> 00:01:31.785
That's the only way a user can build that same mental model

38
00:01:31.785 --> 00:01:33.025
of how the page is laid out.

39
00:01:33.485 --> 00:01:36.265
So the big question is, how do we build that map?

40
00:01:36.655 --> 00:01:39.545
Well, it turns out the web has had this really elegant

41
00:01:40.025 --> 00:01:41.465
solution baked in from the very beginning,

42
00:01:41.765 --> 00:01:44.185
and it's all about something called semantic headings.

43
00:01:44.965 --> 00:01:46.855
Okay? Semantic sounds a little technical,

44
00:01:46.875 --> 00:01:48.695
but all it really means is meaning.

45
00:01:49.235 --> 00:01:50.775
See, we're not just telling the browser

46
00:01:50.835 --> 00:01:53.015
to make some texts look big and bold.

47
00:01:53.385 --> 00:01:55.415
We're giving it a structural meaning.

48
00:01:55.875 --> 00:01:57.855
So an H two tag, it doesn't just say, Hey,

49
00:01:57.855 --> 00:01:59.135
make this text 24 points.

50
00:01:59.515 --> 00:02:02.055
It says, Hey, this is the official start

51
00:02:02.055 --> 00:02:03.975
of a major new section on this page.

52
00:02:03.975 --> 00:02:05.735
It's about meaning, not just looks.

53
00:02:06.435 --> 00:02:08.255
And this is where it gets really cool

54
00:02:08.645 --> 00:02:10.255
because those headings have

55
00:02:10.255 --> 00:02:12.255
that special programmatic meaning

56
00:02:12.775 --> 00:02:15.295
a screen reader can instantly pull all of them out

57
00:02:15.355 --> 00:02:17.535
and just show them to the user as a list.

58
00:02:18.005 --> 00:02:19.855
It's like a popup table of contents.

59
00:02:20.235 --> 00:02:22.695
And just like that, that giant wall of text

60
00:02:23.255 --> 00:02:25.695
transforms into a perfectly navigable outline.

61
00:02:26.105 --> 00:02:28.455
Check it out. This is that superpower in action.

62
00:02:29.055 --> 00:02:31.175
A user can literally just pull up this menu,

63
00:02:31.595 --> 00:02:33.375
see the whole page structure laid out,

64
00:02:33.435 --> 00:02:36.455
and then bam, with one command jump straight

65
00:02:36.455 --> 00:02:37.655
to the eligibility section.

66
00:02:37.965 --> 00:02:39.295
They don't have to listen to all

67
00:02:39.295 --> 00:02:40.335
the stuff that came before it.

68
00:02:40.615 --> 00:02:43.775
I mean, think about what a massive time saver that is. Okay?

69
00:02:43.775 --> 00:02:46.375
So we've got this amazing and table of contents feature,

70
00:02:46.675 --> 00:02:49.175
but for it to actually be useful, it has

71
00:02:49.175 --> 00:02:50.495
to be logical, right?

72
00:02:50.795 --> 00:02:52.735
It needs to follow a few, pretty simple

73
00:02:52.835 --> 00:02:54.455
but really, really crucial rules.

74
00:02:55.275 --> 00:02:57.095
The easiest way to think about this is

75
00:02:57.095 --> 00:02:58.735
to just picture an outline. You'd write

76
00:02:58.735 --> 00:02:59.735
For a school paper.

77
00:02:59.755 --> 00:03:03.085
Seriously, you've got one main title, that's your H one.

78
00:03:03.395 --> 00:03:05.445
Then you have your main points or chapters.

79
00:03:05.495 --> 00:03:06.845
Those are all your H twos

80
00:03:07.185 --> 00:03:09.565
and any supporting details inside those chapters.

81
00:03:09.785 --> 00:03:12.605
Yep, those become H threes, H fours, and so on.

82
00:03:12.865 --> 00:03:14.285
The key thing to remember is

83
00:03:14.285 --> 00:03:16.285
that the number is all about its place in the structure.

84
00:03:16.475 --> 00:03:18.765
It's I importance. It has nothing to do with

85
00:03:18.765 --> 00:03:20.045
how big the text looks on the screen.

86
00:03:20.235 --> 00:03:21.525
Alright? So to keep

87
00:03:21.525 --> 00:03:23.045
That outline nice and logical,

88
00:03:23.475 --> 00:03:24.725
There's one really important

89
00:03:24.875 --> 00:03:26.605
Best practice we should all try

90
00:03:26.605 --> 00:03:27.605
To follow. And it's

91
00:03:27.605 --> 00:03:29.005
this, try not

92
00:03:29.005 --> 00:03:31.165
to skip heading levels as you go down the page.

93
00:03:31.625 --> 00:03:33.965
So for Example, jumping from your main title,

94
00:03:34.185 --> 00:03:35.645
the H one straight to

95
00:03:35.925 --> 00:03:37.125
A subsection, an H

96
00:03:37.125 --> 00:03:39.765
Three, like you see on the right side there, it kind

97
00:03:39.765 --> 00:03:41.085
of breaks the logical flow.

98
00:03:41.275 --> 00:03:43.925
Imagine a screen reader, user hears, heading level one,

99
00:03:44.065 --> 00:03:46.165
and then the very next thing is heading level three.

100
00:03:46.415 --> 00:03:48.525
Their mental map is expecting a level two.

101
00:03:48.525 --> 00:03:49.725
In between when it's missing,

102
00:03:49.985 --> 00:03:52.525
the structure can feel a little broken, a little confusing.

103
00:03:52.795 --> 00:03:53.965
It's a small detail for us,

104
00:03:53.985 --> 00:03:56.205
but it can make a big difference for usability.

105
00:03:56.745 --> 00:03:59.165
And This brings up another super important point.

106
00:03:59.625 --> 00:04:02.245
Not all big, fancy text is actually a heading.

107
00:04:02.625 --> 00:04:03.685
You have to ask yourself,

108
00:04:03.835 --> 00:04:07.325
does this text kick off a totally new distinct section

109
00:04:07.385 --> 00:04:09.645
of content featured collections here on the left?

110
00:04:10.165 --> 00:04:13.285
Absolutely. It's introducing a whole new grid of items.

111
00:04:13.865 --> 00:04:16.085
But a descriptive tagline, like the one on the right,

112
00:04:16.155 --> 00:04:18.845
even if it's styled to be really prominent, that's just part

113
00:04:18.845 --> 00:04:20.085
of the section that came before it.

114
00:04:20.395 --> 00:04:21.965
It's not a new chapter in our book.

115
00:04:22.075 --> 00:04:23.845
It's more like a sentence in the current chapter.

116
00:04:24.555 --> 00:04:26.045
Okay, let's look at a real world

117
00:04:26.045 --> 00:04:27.405
example of how this can go wrong.

118
00:04:27.825 --> 00:04:30.405
So here, the main H one, connect and get inspired.

119
00:04:30.465 --> 00:04:31.645
That's totally correct.

120
00:04:32.065 --> 00:04:35.125
But then notice how it jumps straight to an H three

121
00:04:35.185 --> 00:04:38.605
for the free use section, it skipped H two entirely.

122
00:04:39.385 --> 00:04:41.125
And then that more to discover section,

123
00:04:41.125 --> 00:04:44.085
which is obviously introducing new stuff isn't even marked

124
00:04:44.105 --> 00:04:46.525
as a heading at all for a screen reader user.

125
00:04:46.635 --> 00:04:49.765
This outline is just, well, it's confusing an incomplete.

126
00:04:50.465 --> 00:04:53.685
But now let's contrast that with this perfect example.

127
00:04:54.145 --> 00:04:56.405
See this, we have a nice clear H two

128
00:04:56.405 --> 00:04:58.725
for the whole frequently asked questions section.

129
00:04:59.075 --> 00:05:02.125
Then every category under it, general program information,

130
00:05:02.485 --> 00:05:04.525
deadlines, eligibility, they're all correctly

131
00:05:04.525 --> 00:05:05.605
marked as h threes.

132
00:05:05.795 --> 00:05:07.845
This creates this beautiful, predictable,

133
00:05:07.865 --> 00:05:09.725
and super easy to navigate outline

134
00:05:09.735 --> 00:05:11.285
where the code structure perfectly

135
00:05:11.285 --> 00:05:12.485
mirrors what you see on the screen.

136
00:05:12.755 --> 00:05:14.525
This is what we're aiming for. Alright,

137
00:05:14.745 --> 00:05:15.805
So you're feeling good.

138
00:05:15.805 --> 00:05:17.285
You've got the rules down, right?

139
00:05:17.755 --> 00:05:19.365
Well, hold on. 'cause here comes the

140
00:05:19.365 --> 00:05:20.365
Plot twist. Things

141
00:05:20.365 --> 00:05:23.045
get a little different when

142
00:05:23.045 --> 00:05:24.085
we start talking about mobile.

143
00:05:24.745 --> 00:05:26.855
So what's so fascinating here is this

144
00:05:27.165 --> 00:05:28.895
Huge difference between how iOS

145
00:05:28.895 --> 00:05:30.935
and Android screen readers handle headings.

146
00:05:31.395 --> 00:05:34.935
On an iPhone. A voiceover user hears the whole story heading

147
00:05:34.935 --> 00:05:36.575
Level two, they get the full context.

148
00:05:37.195 --> 00:05:39.775
But on Android, a talkback user just hears heading.

149
00:05:40.155 --> 00:05:41.215
That's It. All

150
00:05:41.215 --> 00:05:42.975
that information about the level, it's just gone.

151
00:05:43.355 --> 00:05:45.735
So what does this mean for us as designers?

152
00:05:46.365 --> 00:05:47.655
It's actually pretty simple.

153
00:05:48.275 --> 00:05:50.855
For an Android user, the difference between an H two

154
00:05:50.855 --> 00:05:52.615
and an H three just doesn't exist,

155
00:05:52.995 --> 00:05:54.215
at least not in what they hear.

156
00:05:54.795 --> 00:05:56.895
But what is still incredibly important

157
00:05:56.895 --> 00:05:58.930
Is that the text is marked as a heading at all

158
00:05:58.995 --> 00:06:01.125
because that's what lets them skip from one heading

159
00:06:01.125 --> 00:06:03.325
to the next, even if they don't know the specific level.

160
00:06:03.905 --> 00:06:06.125
So you might be wondering, how do we handle this?

161
00:06:06.265 --> 00:06:08.605
Do we have to design two totally different experiences?

162
00:06:09.585 --> 00:06:10.925
No way. Absolutely not.

163
00:06:11.265 --> 00:06:14.485
The answer is to design one single logical blueprint

164
00:06:14.485 --> 00:06:16.165
that works for everyone everywhere.

165
00:06:16.785 --> 00:06:18.125
So as a designer, your job

166
00:06:18.125 --> 00:06:19.405
is actually pretty straightforward.

167
00:06:19.745 --> 00:06:22.365
You just have to define the one correct logical hierarchy

168
00:06:22.365 --> 00:06:24.445
from H one down to H six in your designs.

169
00:06:24.445 --> 00:06:26.605
That's it. You create that one perfect outline.

170
00:06:26.705 --> 00:06:29.285
The engineers will take that and implement it, and then iOS

171
00:06:29.285 --> 00:06:31.445
and the web will use all that juicy detail you provided.

172
00:06:31.715 --> 00:06:34.325
Android. It'll just use the basic fact that, yep,

173
00:06:34.325 --> 00:06:35.445
this is a heading to power.

174
00:06:35.505 --> 00:06:37.605
Its navigation. It's one smart design decision

175
00:06:37.605 --> 00:06:38.965
that each platform interprets

176
00:06:38.965 --> 00:06:40.085
in the way that works best for it.

177
00:06:40.555 --> 00:06:42.885
Okay, let's wrap this up with the key takeaways.

178
00:06:42.945 --> 00:06:45.605
Number one, headings are basically a table

179
00:06:45.605 --> 00:06:47.045
of contents for screen reader users.

180
00:06:47.215 --> 00:06:49.565
Super important. Two, always,

181
00:06:49.585 --> 00:06:51.365
always use a logical hierarchy,

182
00:06:51.395 --> 00:06:53.005
just like an outline for a paper.

183
00:06:53.495 --> 00:06:55.205
Three, it's a really good idea

184
00:06:55.305 --> 00:06:56.925
to not skip levels on your way down.

185
00:06:56.985 --> 00:06:58.085
It just keeps things clear.

186
00:06:58.425 --> 00:07:00.565
And finally, number four, you just need

187
00:07:00.565 --> 00:07:01.885
to annotate one good structure

188
00:07:01.985 --> 00:07:03.485
and the platforms will do the heavy lift.

189
00:07:03.865 --> 00:07:06.205
So I'll leave you with this one last thought.

190
00:07:06.505 --> 00:07:08.205
The next time you're designing a page

191
00:07:08.345 --> 00:07:12.245
or a screen, ask yourself, am I designing a clear story

192
00:07:12.465 --> 00:07:14.205
or am I just creating a wall of words?

193
00:07:14.515 --> 00:07:16.965
Because remember, you're not just styling text,

194
00:07:17.265 --> 00:07:19.765
you're crafting a structure, you're telling a story,

195
00:07:20.105 --> 00:07:23.405
and your job is to make sure that story has chapters so

196
00:07:23.405 --> 00:07:25.325
that absolutely everyone can follow along.
